<p>
  Formatting of inline abbreviations is not something that's difficult to do, but getting them to catch the users attention can sometimes be a bit of a challenge.  Twitter Bootstrap
  makes it as easy as adding a class to a &lt;abbr&gt; tag surrounding your abbreviated text, TWB will automatically style it to flow with the rest of your text while still making it
  obvious that there is a reason that text is special.  Like other classes it also works with most html elements
</p>

<h3>This is some header text all about <abbr title="Hypertext Mark Up Language">HTML</abbr> in Twitter Bootstrap</h3>
<p><abbr title="Twitter Bootstrap">TWB</abbr> is a fantastic client side <abbr title="JavaScript">JS</abbr> and <abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr> framework for making great <abbr title="User Interfaces">UI's</abbr></p>

<p>
  You set the text to be displayed in the &lt;abbr&gt; tag by setting it's <code>title="..."</code> attribute to the text you want to display when the user hovers over the abbreviation. 
  you can also add the optional <code>class="initialism"</code> to your tag, which will give it a slightly smaller font size.
</p>

