<p>
  Formatting and address and contact details is equally as easy, for this you use the &lt;address&gt; html tag with &lt;br/&gt; tags to break each line as the following example shows:
</p>

<address>
  <strong>Digital Solutions UK.</strong><br>
  123 A street, Suite 600<br>
  A Town, A County<br>
  <abbr title="Phone">P:</abbr> (123) 456-7890
</address>
 
<address>
  <strong>Peter Shaw</strong><br>
  <a href="mailto:#">peter.shaw@digital-solutions.me.uk</a>
</address>

<pre>

  &lt;address&gt;
    &lt;strong&gt;Digital Solutions UK.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
    123 A street, Suite 600&lt;br&gt;
    A Town, A County&lt;br&gt;
    &lt;abbr title="Phone"&gt;P:&lt;/abbr&gt; (123) 456-7890
  &lt;/address&gt;
 
  &lt;address&gt;
    &lt;strong&gt;Peter Shaw&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br&gt;
    &lt;a href="mailto:#"&gt;peter.shaw@digital-solutions.me.uk&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;/address&gt;

</pre>

<p>
  The effect may not be immediate and many of you might be thinking I can do that easily using what I've seen so far, using the &lt;address&gt; element has an advantage though, and that
  is the new semantic layout model used by HTML5.  In future the major search engines will start to take notice of things like this in order to show your companys contact details in 
  search listings.  Semantic layout and micro-formats are going to become increasingly important in tomorrows world of interconnected web applications and some sites such as Google 
  are already starting to index and take advantage of constructs like this found in the sites they index.
</p>

