<p>
  The last part of this section is blockquotes.  For those of you who don't know what blockquotes are, they are the small snippets of text often seen in books and on sites where the author 
  quotes someone's famous words, or displays a marketing quote.  Consider the following example:
</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>I Think there is a worldwide market for maybe five computers.</p>
  <p><small>IBM President Thomas J. Watson</small></p>
</blockquote>

<pre>
  &lt;blockquote&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;I Think there is a worldwide market for maybe five computers.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;&lt;small&gt;IBM President Thomas J. Watson&lt;/small&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/blockquote&gt;
</pre>

<p>
  Like the &lt;address&gt; tag, &lt;blockquote&gt; is a new tag in HTML5 and like the other tags, Twitter Bootstrap provides out of the box styling for it.  To create your blockquote 
  all you simply need to do is wrap your regular HTML content inside a set of &lt;blockquote&gt; html elements.
</p>
